solution.p:
The first term is 6, so we have a_1 = 6. To find each subsequent term, we add 3 to the previous term:
\begin{aligned}[t] a_2 \amp = a_1 + 3 = 6 + 3 = 9\\ a_3 \amp = a_2 + 3 = 9 + 3 = 12\\ a_4 \amp = a_3 + 3 = 12 + 3 = 15\\ \end{aligned}
The first four terms are 6, 9, 12, and 15.

subsection.p:
We have found a recursive definition for an arithmetic sequence, but we can also find a non-recursive definition. That is, we can find a formula for the general term. Consider an arithmetic sequence with first term a and common difference d. The
\begin{aligned}[t] \text{first term is}~~~~~~ \amp a\\ \text{second term is}~~~~~~ \amp a + d\\ \text{third term is}~~~~~~ \amp a + d + d = a + 2d\\ \text{fourth term is}~~~~~~ \amp a + d + d + d = a + 3d\\ n^{\text{th}}~ \text{term is}~~~~~~ \amp a + d + d + \cdots + d = a + (n - 1)d \end{aligned}
Thus, we have the following property.

If C_n represents the number of contestants after n rounds of competition, then
\begin{aligned}[t] C_1 \amp = 1024 (\dfrac{1}{2}) = 512\\ C_2 \amp = 512 (\dfrac{1}{2}) = 1024 (\dfrac{1}{2})^2 = 256\\ C_3 \amp = 256 (\dfrac{1}{2}) = 1024 (\dfrac{1}{2})^3 = 128\\ \end{aligned}
In general C_n = 1024 (\dfrac{1}{2})^n

solution.p:
The first term is 64, so we have a_1=64. To find each subsequent term, we multipy the previous term by \dfrac{5}{4}.
\begin{aligned}[t] a_2 \amp = (\dfrac{5}{4})a_1 = (\dfrac{5}{4})(64) = 80\\ a_3 \amp = (\dfrac{5}{4})a_2 = (\dfrac{5}{4})(80) = 100\\ a_4 \amp = (\dfrac{5}{4})a_3 = (\dfrac{5}{4})(100) = 125\\ \end{aligned}
The first four terms are 64, 80, 100, and 125.

